Don't scare people like that. The main way it promotes fat gain is by simply making your body more responsive to insulin, so you naturally start putting on more weight by eating carbs.
However, pio can force your body to create new fat deposits according to hormone levels. Our bodies are pretty lazy, so even if you have perfect E levels, your body will put a decent chunk of fat to fat deposits you already have which might be the male/android type. Pio will force your body to prioritise female/gynoid fat distribution. But it won't use up all the stem cells! It's pretty safe in this regard.
This >>29032491 is correct, but you definitely shouldn't take it for longer than 1y, I'm planning to take a break after 6-8 months, and, if needed, I'll repeat the course after a 6mo break.
Also, watch out for the side effects, don't be paranoid, but if you notice that something feels off, the either lower the dose or straight up quit if lowering didn't help.

Goal of the thread: Open your window for 10-20 minutes, maybe have a walk if the weather allows.
Daily goals can be repeated. Remember to keep score, it can only go up!

>What is this thread for?
Getting better is hard, and sucks. A lot. It does not get easier doing it alone.
Share resources and experiences with combating depression, anxiety, personal issues, achieving or maintaining a healthy weight, etc.
>Why is this thread /lgbt/?
Struggles with mental and physical health are an indisputable part of /lgbt/ life, be it from dysphoria, social pressure, heartbreak, or just unfortunate lifestyle choices.
>Notes to consider:
Please be civil. Shame is your greatest enemy in fighting urges of self abuse (be it sh, drugs, or just self deprecation). Relapsing into bad and unhealthy habits is to be expected, the goal is to increase the average amount of time it takes between relapses. Any improvement is a victory no matter how small. Your worth and right to get better are non-negotiable. And most importantly:
WE ARE NOT THERAPISTS, WE DON'T REPLACE MEDICATION
>Note on advice
Generic advice won't necessarily help you in particular, but for those it does it is an essential foundation to build future progress on, not a miracle cure. Do not underestimate the effects subtle changes to your lifestyle can have. Try first, keep us posted on your progress, build from there.

We are *always* short on self help resources, so if anything was useful to you, let us know!
Since the OP is getting too long I moved all resources into their own post, see below!

>>29027374
1) bica is pretty safe, and most of the risks come from it being used at chemotherapy doses which probably won't apply to you. likewise, cancer patients aren't exactly the healthiest cohort to begin with. it can be managed fairly effectively by getting LFTs, since in about 0.1% of people it can cause liver damage, for everyone else, it's fine. it's a monitoring thing. on bica you want LFTs, you want E levels, you want T levels, and you want SHBG so you can figure out your free T since bica elevates that.

2) she won't up your prescription. you'll need to get levels done first. even so, you're better to just switching to sublingual without telling her, rather than swallowing the pills, since that will give you better levels than whatever shit she'll offer you.

3) you can't prevent her pressuring you. just point out that finasteride is NOT an antiandrogen, it's a 5a reductase inhibitor which simply prevents DHT from being produced. it's best for treating male pattern baldness, not for reducing T levels which is what you want if you're taking oral E
